 post out here because I think I derailed Dels post about the IRO vote in the General section.  It was just a question I had.  I had no intention to start a big discussion, sorry.  Also, this may ramble a bit.  I’ll try not to wander too much.  I will also bring up points that represent what some folks have said in the past without giving names.  I’m talking about these points and not about the folks behind them.  Those are two very different topics; and I don’t bash people.  Lastly, I’m not trying to convert anyone, just expressing some views for others to think on.<br>
<br>
Where to begin…<br>
<br>
History…To my knowledge, when Brell was young in it’s raiding days, only a handful of guilds were capable of these feats.  Most communication was handled in game between these guilds and the world was good.  As time progressed, it was decided that a better forum was needed to communicate and to better organize the sharing of these “resources” and this led to the creation of the Brell site.  (.ed  I really hate seeing folks call the mobs and their loot resources.  It just feels wrong to me.)  A calendar was placed on the Brell site for scheduling raids and to provide a reference for planning guild events.  Over time, as more and more players became raid capable (by level) and more guilds were created, players were actually directed to the Brell site to organize and plan their raids.<br>
<br>
Here is where my understanding of history differs from what some folks are now saying.  People say this site was never intended to function this way.  It was only created for a few guilds to communicate.  This can not be true.  Once I became raid fodder, I was told by several folks to start visiting the Brell site to raid.  While it’s true that some folks are still unaware of this site, this site has become “the place” to communicate and plan raids.  If it was truly intended for the use of a few guilds, it should have been locked down and the rotations never started in a public forum; an dplayer should not of been encouraged to go to the site.<br>
<br>
Today…Our server population has finally reached a saturation point in regards to raiding certain mobs.  Brell has been in existence long enough for a lot of folks to have more than one alt who is raid capable..  Competition for items and quest junk has escalated to the point of frustrating most of the player base to some degree or another.  There is no “end game” to EQ.  There are only two ways to distinguish yourself in this world; 1. Level, and 2. Gear.  Because of this, Verant controls the rate at which items enter the game through spawn times and loot tables.  This is where the competition in the game comes from for most folks.  When you look back on “epic” encounters, they are not truly that challenging.  (To me, anything that fights the same way every time is not a challenge.  It’s more of a puzzle.)<br>
<br>
Finger Pointing…With rotations being stretched and doomsayers raising their voices, change is being forced upon the community.  Some folks point to the IROs as the source of evil.  It’s not.  On the three (3) current rotations, there are a total of eight (<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  IROs, hardly a fraction of the total number of slots taken.  However, one IRO is currently on two (2) lists and should be dropped from one list.  The biggest problem comes from the number of guilds which are created each week for all the alts.  This is the way that the rotations are being abused, not by IROs.  But then it comes to how you view characters in the game.  Do you view the character as the individual or the player behind the characters as the individual?  ( I view each character as an individual.  Though some folks abuse the use of their alts in the game.)  There are few honest folks in this game, imho.  Everyone has their own agenda and will bend things for their own ends.  (My agenda is to finish my epic.)<br>
<br>
Just where the heck is she going?<br>
<br>
Well, I realize there is a lot of this game that I’ll never see.  I’m basically a social gnat, but it’s my own fault.  (No, not looking for pity.  It’s going somewhere, honest.)  I used to think that the rotation system would be the only way I would ever have a chance at seeing some of the encounters.  But the server is just too crowded now.  Everyone and their brother has an alt now which further crowds the server.  Due to this fact alone, the rotations will no longer work.  It kind of hurts to say this, but the server should just turn FCFS.  All the lists should be dropped.  However, I do strongly feel that a definition of FCFS should be agreed upon.  The main sticking point would be the definition of the first to arrive there in force.  Define “in force.”  The planes should still be scheduled though, but the two  (2) week limit should be raised to three (3) weeks.  <br>
<br>
There is no solution for the rotation list.  Removing IROs does nothing.  Forcing guilds to co-host will not be agreed to.  No one likes to do the paper work involved in validating her/his raid.  I honestly think there is no solution when you really look at it.<br>
<br>
Sit back for a couple of days and think on it.  Yes, FCFS does have it’s problems with potential farming.  You just have to come to the realization that you will not get everything that you want.  (hehe..I am 56 and still see twinks with better gear than me.)  With FCFS, we’ll just have to rely on folks talking in game to work stuff out on conflicts.  I just hope that some folks will still feel inclined to share.<br>
<br>
Tatter D'Malion <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unicophorus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nicophorus</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://homepages.go.com/~aela_eq/Shield.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Less Talk, More Fight</span><br>  Posts: 814<br> <font color=#CC9900>(5/24/01 9:04:48 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://homepages.go.com/~aela_eq/Shield.gif border=0></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: My Final Musings on Rotations, hopefully…</span><hr size=1> While I don't agree with every one of your reasons, I certainly agree with your conclusion.  <br>
<br>
The current system is only as fair as the people using it are.  <br>
<br>
While many of the users of the system DO use it appropriately, a significant percentage do NOT use it appropriately.<br>
<br>
Any system of reform we put in place (limiting Indy's, making guilds double up for raids, etc) tends to punish the people that will FOLLOW that reform... the people exploiting will simply continue to exploit.<br>
<br>
The system is unenforcable.  Banning exploiters will only enourage them to completely ignore the system.  Reform punishes the people not exploiting... thus eventually encouraging THEM to not use the system.<br>
<br>
Brell is 19 months old (or thereabouts)... over that time most of the playerbase has brought at least one character in raidworthy level range.  The fastest levelers have done it several times over.  The result is that at most times playing over 1/3 of the population is in a level range contending for the resources we 'reserve.'  The number of Independants, small guilds, uber guilds, European players, Asian players, American players isnt the problem... the number of players times the number of months divided by the number of resources IS the problem.<br>
<br>
There is no method for reforming this system that gives a fair shake to the large guilds, small guilds, Indy's, Europeans, Asians, Americans, etc. playing this game.  Any series of reforms asks one of those groups to suffer a lack of opportunity for the benefit of another group... that wouldn't be a problem if the notion involved shared sacrifice and shared opportunity, but it doesn't...<br>
<br>
The majority of our dungeons are FCFS.  The majority of our dungeons cause NO problems in playstyle.  A small percentage of our resources (sorry, its the only word that fits) ARE reservable.  These reservable resources cause almost 100% of the problems.<br>
<br>
There are too many upper levels and too many resources for one or two 'uberguilds' to dominate a server as was the case on many servers in old Norrath (pre-Kunark).  However, there are too many upperlevels and too few resources for a simple rotation system to work.  More landmass is coming which will help, and a server split MIGHT be coming which will help further... that said, there isn't really a benefit to reservations or rotations any longer.<br>
<br>
Reforming the system will likely only hasten its demise.  Doing nothing to the system will likely hasten its demise.  I'd venture that allowing for its demise and figuring out how to civily go about the new disorder would be prudent.<br>
<br>
Personally... drop the dragon rotation... drop the planar reservations.  Let people organize and play the game.  There is now plenty of items and zones for the small to midsize player to get a fair shake.  Organizing isn't hard.  Maybe we should just put the old system away.<br>
